description: The Berlin is suspected to have been scuttled on 31 May 1946 with chemical weapons onboard.

In this area (near Zmeiny Island and in the vicinity of Crimea), the Soviet Union disposed of one or more of the following chemical agents: Levinstein mustard gas, Zaikov mustard gas, viscous solutions of mustard gas and lewisite, hydrocyanic acid

Dumping in this area occurred from 1945 to 1965. From August 1945-December 1946: The British Autorities in Germany; August 1947-January 1948: The Soviet Military Authority in Germany dumped 11000T of CW; 1959-July 1965: The GDR dumped a total of 60T
The Bremse is suspected to have been scuttled with chemical weapons onboard.

Munitions dumped near this location include: 5,920 mustard bombs, 591 adamsite bombs, 479 CN (chloroacetophenone) bombs, 671 mustard gas artillery shells, 61 adamsite artillery shells, 36 CN artillery shells, 314 mustard filled high-explosive bombs.

The German Marinefï¿½hrprahm (Landing Craft) F-192 was scuttled near this location on 10 May 1946.  A Norwegian study of sea-dumped chemical weapons in the Skagerrak strait lists the F-192 as being suspected of carrying chemical weapons.

Reports indicate the possibility of CW dumping conducted on 28 April 1945 in the southern section of the Flensborg Fjord by German vessels en route to the Little Belt area. It is estimated that 1200T of chemical munitions may have been dumped.

Following several incidents in the 1950s, chemical warfare materials were suspected to have been dumped at a depth of between 260-260 ft of water alongside conventional munitions within a region of about 100 hectares.

Dumping of CW by the Soviet Military Adminstration in Germany [2] occurred near these coordinates in an area of 141,610 hectacres [2], at a depth of between 300-450 ft, between May and September, 1947, and included 2,000T of chemical munitions
The H.C. Horn is suspected to have been scuttled on 26 May 1946 with chemical weapons onboard.
The Krysser Leipzig was scuttled on 16 December 1946 while carrying 1000T of suspected chemical munitions.

In 1961, hydrogen chloride and phosgene gas containers were loose dumped near this location. Conventional munitions have also been recovered at this site including 15 torpedoes, 1431 10.5 cm piece of artillery shells, and 382 U.S. 20 lbs. cluster bombs.
A ship designated M-16 is suspected to have been scuttled in this area on 18 May 1946 while carrying chemical weapons.
A ship designated M-280 is suspected to have been scuttled in this area on 26 July 1946 while carrying chemical weapons.
A ship designated M-522 is suspected to have been scuttled in this area 18 May 1946 while carrying chemical weapons.

Crews unintentionally dropped an undisclosed number of mustard bombs into the Manfredonia Bay, while unloading a transport vessel. Some of these munitions were later recovered and intentionally dumped 54mi further from shore at undisclosed coordinates.
The Marcy, a German freighter, was scuttled on August 24, 1948, at these coordinates, while carrying 2800T of chemical weapons. This was the final scuttling as part of Operation Davy Jones' Locker.

Swedish authorities confirm that ~22,000T of chemical munitions within eight scuttled naval vessels rest on the sea floor. Investigators found a significant quantity of mustard gas tolerant microbiota, indicating the presence of mustard gas.
Munitions including an unknown number of M47 mustard bombs are suspected of having been dumped at unknown location(s) in the Mediterranean Sea.  1945.

The United States may have disposed of phosgene, hydrogen cyanide, and cyanogen chloride in the Adratic Sea near the town of Bari during the winter of 1945. In addition, the US may have also dumped lewisite and/or mustard bombs in the same area in April

Over an unknown period of time, between 716,000 and 1.32 million tons of munitions were dumped at this location.  Salvage operations in the 1950s and later discovered numerous shells, bombs, and other munitions containing mustard gas and others chemicals
The Philip Heiniken, a German freighter, was scuttled on July 24, 1948, will carrying 2240T of chemical weapons. This scuttling took place as part of Operation Davy Jones' Locker.

Site is located ~60mi west of Hebrides Seamount, inside of Rockall Trough. Exact coordinates are undetermined. Contents of site are unknown. Chemical munition disposal at this location reported by the Oslo-Paris Commission.
Three ships designated S-7, S-9, and S-12 are suspected to have been scuttled in this area on 2 May 1946 while carrying chemical weapons.
A ship designated T-21 is suspected to have been scuttled on 16 Demcember 1946 in this area while carrying chemical weapons.
A ship designated T-37 is suspected to have been scuttled in this area on 26 July 1946 while carrying chemical weapons.
Two ships, designated T-38 and T-39, are suspected to have been scuttled in this area on 10 May 1946, while carrying chemical weapons.
A ship designated TF-1 is suspected to have been scuttled in this area on 2 May 1946 while carrying chemical weapons.
The exact types of munitions is unknown, but dumping took place from 1956 to 1959. The current knowledge on this possible dumping site is limited to information gained from single sources.
The Torpedojager T-65 was an incomplete German torpedo boat scuttled near these coordinates while likely containing assorted chemical weapons.
The Herald notes that three ships were loaded with mustard, phosgene and tabun munitions, then scuttled in the area (between 50 and 100mi west of the island).

The former Soviet Union dumped one or more of the following material into the Black Sea, west of Sevastopol: Levinstein mustard gas, Zaikov mustard gas, lewisite, varied forms of lewisite, mustard mixtures, viscid solutions of mustard gas and lewisite.
On August 7, 1944, the William L. Marcy was scuttled near these coordinates.  The ship is believed to have contained an unknown quantity of chemical weapons.
A ship designated Z-34 is suspected to have been scuttled on 26 March 1946 in this area while carrying chemical weapons.

Dump site is between 12 and 19mi from the Russian and/or Georgian shores. Dumping was conducted by the former Soviet Union in between 230 and 265ft of water. Material dumped includes one or more of the following chemical agents: Levinstein mustard gas, Z
